What AWS Lambda actually is?

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OJrxbr9ebDE

s3 trigger with lamda when file upload

It’s a serverless compute service:

You upload your code (called a function)
AWS runs it only when triggered
You don’t manage servers, scaling, or infrastructure

⚙️ How it works
You write a function (Python, Node.js, Java, etc.)
You set a trigger (event)
Lambda runs your code automatically

Common triggers:
File upload to Amazon S3
HTTP request via Amazon API Gateway
Database updates (e.g., DynamoDB)
Scheduled jobs (cron)


All triggers:

+---------------------+----------------------------------------------+
| Trigger             | Example                                      |
+---------------------+----------------------------------------------+
| S3                  | File uploaded → resize image                 |
| API Gateway         | HTTP request → return response               |
| DynamoDB            | Record changed → notify user                 |
| SQS                 | Message in queue → process it                |
| SNS                 | Notification → send email                    |
| CloudWatch Events   | Every 5 mins → run job                       |
| Cognito             | User signup → send welcome email             |
| CodePipeline        | Build done → notify team                     |
+---------------------+----------------------------------------------+


How it works:

Trigger happens
    ↓
AWS spins up container
    ↓
Runs your function
    ↓
Returns result
    ↓
Container destroyed
    ↓
You pay only for execution time ✅

 Real world use cases:

✅ Image resizing when uploaded to S3
✅ Send welcome email on user signup
✅ Process payments asynchronously
✅ ETL data pipelines
✅ Scheduled reports (cron)
✅ Webhook handlers
✅ Chat bots

❌ Long running processes (use ECS/EKS)
❌ Heavy computation (use EC2)
❌ Persistent connections (use EC2)
❌ Large file processing > 15min

Here are the top 5 must-know Lambda interview topics:

1. Cold Start

What:
  First invocation → AWS spins up container → slow
  Subsequent calls → container warm → fast

Why it happens:
  Lambda scales to zero when not in use
  New container needed on first call

How to fix:
  Provisioned concurrency → pre-warm containers
  Ping every 5 mins → keep warm
  Smaller package size → faster startup
  Python/Node → faster than Java

2. Lambda vs EC2

Lambda:
  ✅ no server management
  ✅ scales to zero
  ✅ pay per execution
  ❌ max 15 min
  ❌ stateless
  ❌ cold start

EC2:
  ✅ long running
  ✅ stateful
  ✅ full control
  ❌ pay even idle
  ❌ manage yourself

